      "message": "The reason people typically `using std::swap` is a little different than just convenience.  The main reason it\u0027s used is that it allows you to write `swap(x,y)` and have that pick up ::swap() if one exists for the types of x and y, or fall back to std::swap() if one doesn\u0027t exist.\n\nThe rest should all be strictly convenience, but the using idiom for std::swap is really an idiom about correctly picking up overrides.\n\nThe thing that will make Fiddle code read most orthodox is to continue to refer to things in std:: with that prefix, and when you need to use std::swap(), put a `using std::swap;` declaration as tightly scoped as reasonable.",
